Podolsky argued  that the Siklov spaces (a general
family of spacetimes containing the
Kaigorodov space) can be viewed as an  space-time with a
propagating gravitational wave, whose spatial direction rotates at a
constant velocity in orthonormal frames parellely transported along
timelike geodesics. He also showed that these spaces have a
pp-singularity at : the geodesic deviation equation becomes
singular, but the square of the Riemann tensor remains finite. This
occurs at  in (), which corresponds to the brane horizon
for us. We shall show in section  that
this pp-singularity, which reprensents the divergence of tidal forces as one approaches
the brane, can remain after taking the Penrose limit. 


Clearly () can be interpreted as a wave propagating on the
horospheres of , but  is not covariantly
constant. However this form of the metric suggests the rescalings:
 
