Although  is null, Killing and hence geodetic, this is
not a Penrose limit, since the metric is not rescaled by 
to yield conservation of the affine parameter along . The
corresponding Penrose limit, as explained in the next section, yields
flat space. Thus () can be interpreted as an
infinite unrescaled boost of the Kaigorodov spacetime, which yields
. The dynamical interpretation of this boost is unclear though. (One also gets the  metric by rescaling all the
coordinates by  and letting ). In
, it is shown that the boundary CFT energy-momentum
tensor of the Kaigorodov space is a constant null momentum density,
therefore it is the Kaigorodov space which should be thought of as an
infinitely boosted  spacetime, and not the reverse. It will be 
more relevant in our analysis to consider Kaigorodov spaces just as  spacetimes with a
gravitational wave perturbation.

In this sense, the near horizon limits: M/D-brane  and
M/D-pp-brane  show a nice
geometric behaviour of the world-volume gravitational waves under the limiting
procedure: indeed the null direction of propagation of the wave on the
brane,  in (
